<bioghist altrender="history" encodinganalog="545" id="a2">
<head>History</head>
<p><corpname>Cole and Ambler</corpname> was one of the more than twenty hat manufacturers in <geogname>Bethel, Connecticut</geogname>, during the nineteenth century. [<persname>Edward J. Gallagher</persname>, <title render="italic">History of Bethel, Connecticut</title>, New Haven: Technical Planning Associates, 1969, p. 2-10.]</p>
<p>Little secondary source material concerning the company has been located, and the reliability of what has been found is questionable. <title render="italic">A History of Bethel</title>, Lewis and <persname>Laura Goodsell</persname>, eds., (1976), state only that <corpname>Cole and Ambler</corpname> burned down in 1805 [p. 43]. It is possible that either the manufacturing building was destroyed at this time, and that the company re-established at another location, or that the date in the book is wrong and the company was burned out at a later date. Since the <corpname>Cole and Ambler</corpname> records start fifty years after the company was supposedly destroyed, the Bethel reference cannot be true as published.</p>
</bioghist>
<scopecontent encodinganalog="520" id="a3">
<head>Scope and Content</head>
<p>The collection consists of financial records of the company such as journals, ledger and accounts received and paid in addition to payroll and employee accounts. Also included are Sales records and ordering materials.</p>
</scopecontent>
